"1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","about 1320":"circa 1320","Plenderleith, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Plenderleith, Roxburghshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"8 January 1294–":"8 January 1294–Deceased","1294–Male":"1294–Deceased","1282–1326":"1282–1326","1323–1340":"1323–1340","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1326":"1326","8 January 1294":"8 January 1294","1323":"1323","1265":"1265","1340":"1340","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","about 1320":"about 1320","Plenderleith, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Plenderleith, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wishart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (eastern and central Scotland): of Norman origin, from the Anglo-Norman French form, <i>Wischard</i>, of the Old French personal name <i>Guiscard</i>. This was formed in Normandy from the Old Norse elements <i>vizkr</i> ‘wise’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, bold’ (or possibly the Old French suffix <i>-ard</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Wishard","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Wishart  . This surname is very rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Wisehart","meanings":["Probably an Americanized form of German <b>Weisshardt</b>, from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wīs</i> ‘wise’ + <i>hart</i> ‘strong, hard’.","Perhaps an altered form of Scottish   Wishart  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Plenderleith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish: locative name from Plenderleith in Oxnam (Perths)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When George William Wishart of Plenderleith was born on 8 January 1294, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Wishart - Baron of Plenderleith, was 34 and his mother, Johanna de Plenderleith - Baroness of Plenderleith, was 29. He married Alice De Erskine about 1320, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"8 January 1294–":"8. jaanuar 1294–Surnud","1294–Male":"1294–Surnud","1282–1326":"1282–1326","1323–1340":"1323–1340","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1326":"1326","8 January 1294":"8. jaanuar 1294","1323":"1323","1265":"1265","1340":"1340","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","about 1320":"umbes 1320","Plenderleith, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Plenderleith, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"8 January 1294–":"8. tammikuuta 1294–Kuollut","1294–Male":"1294–Kuollut","1282–1326":"1282–1326","1323–1340":"1323–1340","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1326":"1326","8 January 1294":"8. tammikuuta 1294","1323":"1323","1265":"1265","1340":"1340","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","128